01:22.095 --> 01:24.363
♪

01:28.001 --> 01:29.434
(METALLIC CLANGING)

01:33.039 --> 01:35.073
GUNTHER: Now, raccoons are destructive.

01:35.075 --> 01:39.278
To get rid of a destructive
pest, you have to lure them in.

01:39.280 --> 01:40.512
Good morning.

01:40.514 --> 01:43.582
GUNTHER: <i>Best way to do that...</i>
with food.

01:43.584 --> 01:44.850
Can I make you some breakfast?

01:44.852 --> 01:47.419
GUNTHER: <i>Now, this took
some trial and error.</i>

01:47.421 --> 01:51.029
Eggs and bacon. Pancakes?

01:52.326 --> 01:54.960
Or I could just do French toast.

01:54.962 --> 01:57.829
Not hungry.

02:01.534 --> 02:04.303
GUNTHER: <i>You got to find
just the right bait.</i>

02:07.607 --> 02:10.576
<i>But I figured it out.</i> Cat food.

02:10.578 --> 02:13.712
'Cause raccoons love eating cat food.

02:13.714 --> 02:15.414
So do cats!

02:15.416 --> 02:18.217
- Hey, Phyllis.
- You can't do this.

02:18.219 --> 02:19.785
You're endangering neighborhood pets.

02:19.787 --> 02:23.488
This is private property, ma'am.
We can set whatever traps we want.

02:23.490 --> 02:25.457
Then I'm not letting Caramel
anywhere near this place.

02:25.459 --> 02:28.460
Then everybody wins.

02:29.696 --> 02:33.298
Damn rich people. Too much
free time on their hands.

02:33.300 --> 02:34.900
TESSA: <i>You have to be kidding me.</i>

02:34.902 --> 02:37.269
There must be lots of belts
that look like this.

02:37.271 --> 02:39.972
But look at the doghouse
in the background.

02:39.974 --> 02:41.206
It's half-painted.

02:41.208 --> 02:43.675
And the belt from the concrete had
a smear of green paint on it.

02:43.677 --> 02:45.210
It's the same green paint.

02:45.212 --> 02:46.445
This is Cam we're talking about.

02:46.447 --> 02:47.779
He draws a cartoon frog for a living.

02:47.781 --> 02:51.984
When he sees a homeless guy, he gives
him all the money in his pockets,

02:51.986 --> 02:54.620
and now you're telling me he
was a teenage serial killer?

02:54.622 --> 02:56.855
No, Tess, all I'm saying
is that that is the belt

02:56.857 --> 03:00.959
that was used to strangle David
Morales, and that is Cam wearing it.

03:00.961 --> 03:03.528
(EXHALES): Oh. Maybe...

03:03.530 --> 03:06.164
someone else had access to it.

03:06.166 --> 03:09.134
- Or Cam borrowed it.
- Yeah.

03:09.136 --> 03:11.870
- Or lent it.
- Yeah, of course, of course.

03:11.872 --> 03:14.373
Look, I can shut all this down,

03:14.375 --> 03:16.975
but I'm gonna need a
sample of Cam's DNA.

03:16.977 --> 03:22.047
And that way we can prove that
the blood on the belt isn't his.

03:27.053 --> 03:28.687
I'll talk to him.

03:31.524 --> 03:34.593
MADELINE: <i>Let's get this over with.</i>

03:34.595 --> 03:38.864
- Garrett won't be joining us.
- Shocker.

03:41.434 --> 03:44.503
First, your father left the
entirety of his assets to me,

03:44.505 --> 03:48.707
but he would want you to
be taken care of always.

03:48.709 --> 03:50.942
He loved you so much.

03:50.944 --> 03:54.880
So whatever you need, come to me.

03:54.882 --> 03:58.550
Your father also left me in
charge of Hawthorne Concrete,

03:58.552 --> 04:00.352
and I've decided to sell.

04:00.354 --> 04:02.554
What?

04:02.556 --> 04:07.025
- The company is Dad's legacy.
- It's too much to handle alone.

04:07.027 --> 04:11.163
In fact, we've been talking about selling
because of your father's... condition.

04:11.165 --> 04:15.534
- He trusted me to do what's best...
- But maybe there's a way to keep...

04:15.536 --> 04:19.137
...and he would expect the entire
family to support my decision.

04:19.139 --> 04:20.738
(SIGHS)

04:20.741 --> 04:27.212
- Are there any other questions?
- I have a question for Cam.

04:30.750 --> 04:33.285
Brady hasn't shown this to anyone.

04:33.287 --> 04:35.887
If Cam gives a DNA sample,
he won't have to.

04:39.926 --> 04:42.661
- I don't even remember that belt.
- MADELINE: I do.

04:42.663 --> 04:46.498
It was expensive and you barely had
it a week before you got paint on it,

04:46.500 --> 04:49.701
so I put it into the Goodwill
pile for Gunther to drop off.

04:49.703 --> 04:52.104
Well, it could have wound up
in anyone's hands after that.

04:52.106 --> 04:54.272
I mean, including Gunther's.

04:54.274 --> 04:57.075
Could that box of bells in the
shed have belonged to him?

04:59.612 --> 05:03.482
I just thought it was your
father's creepy, old memorabilia,

05:03.484 --> 05:05.817
but I guess it's possible.

05:05.819 --> 05:08.420
Gunther? He's such a nice guy.

05:08.422 --> 05:11.156
God, Tess, everyone's such a
nice guy in your world...

05:11.158 --> 05:12.157
What?

05:12.159 --> 05:14.693
I'm a nice guy, but the
police want my DNA.

05:14.695 --> 05:17.729
Dad's a nice guy and we still
wonder about him. God forbid

05:17.731 --> 05:19.197
anybody doubt whether
Garrett's a nice guy,

05:19.199 --> 05:20.532
even though he looks
like an axe murderer...

05:20.534 --> 05:22.134
- What is wrong with you?
- Let's face it,

05:22.136 --> 05:24.536
someone around here is
not that nice of a guy!

05:24.538 --> 05:27.472
Stop it. Okay?

05:27.474 --> 05:28.607
Now, listen to me.

05:28.609 --> 05:32.644
Cam wore a belt that went to Goodwill.
That's it.

05:32.646 --> 05:35.180
- You don't owe anybody anything.
- And you should

05:35.182 --> 05:36.982
never give a DNA sample
without a warrant.

05:36.984 --> 05:39.985
The cops can spin the results
to fit any narrative they want.

05:39.987 --> 05:41.086
Brady wouldn't.

05:41.088 --> 05:44.790
Plus, you'll be in the
system for all eternity.

05:44.792 --> 05:47.692
They'll test your blood for everything.

05:50.897 --> 05:52.397
All right.

05:53.924 --> 05:55.112
Tell Brady it's a no.

05:56.870 --> 05:58.670
Okay.

05:59.792 --> 06:02.140
What is Jack doing?

06:05.928 --> 06:08.596
Is that Harper's doll?

06:15.588 --> 06:16.855
What are you doing?

06:16.857 --> 06:21.626
Gunther says you have to put something
in the cage that the animal wants.

06:21.628 --> 06:25.330
You're trying to trap your cousin?

06:29.869 --> 06:32.437
(GASPS)

06:34.974 --> 06:37.509
- Therapy.
- Yeah.

06:37.511 --> 06:41.046
TOM: <i>The kid isdisturbed.</i> Imagine
if Harper had crawled in there.

06:41.048 --> 06:44.716
The whole family's a mess
in the wake of everything,

06:44.718 --> 06:48.353
and I still can't believe my mom
is already selling the company.

06:48.355 --> 06:50.522
What if there was a way to
still keep it in the family?

06:50.524 --> 06:54.526
- What do you mean?
- What if I bought it?

06:55.995 --> 06:59.297
- What do you think?
- (CHUCKLES)

06:59.299 --> 07:05.203
We agreed you'd devote yourself
full-time to supporting my run.

07:05.205 --> 07:08.373
- We're in this together.
- Are we?

07:09.909 --> 07:13.879
I need you. I do.

07:13.881 --> 07:17.015
I-I can't win this election without you.

07:17.017 --> 07:19.251
We're losing ground to Conley.

07:19.253 --> 07:22.787
He brought in one of Obama's
social media consultants.

07:22.789 --> 07:25.323
I need your help.

07:25.325 --> 07:29.628
Not just with the girls,
with the campaign.

07:30.628 --> 07:34.900
LINDA: <i>This is promising.</i> The
belt found in the tunnel...

07:34.902 --> 07:38.637
that particular style was only sold
in five stores starting in '95.

07:38.639 --> 07:41.339
We get sales records. We check
those against who was present

07:41.341 --> 07:43.174
when the concrete was poured... boom.

07:43.176 --> 07:47.345
Yeah, yeah, "boom" is right.

07:47.347 --> 07:49.714
I can't just sit on this photo, Tess.

07:49.716 --> 07:51.950
It's a matter of time before
somebody here realizes

07:51.952 --> 07:54.619
that someone in your
family had that belt.

07:54.621 --> 07:56.154
What do you expect me to do?

07:56.156 --> 07:58.056
You got to get Cam to
reconsider giving his DNA.

07:58.058 --> 07:59.424
I told you, it's a no.

07:59.426 --> 08:01.726
It's the fastest way
to shut all this down.

08:01.728 --> 08:03.328
Find another way.

08:03.330 --> 08:05.997
Fine, you can provide your own DNA.

08:05.999 --> 08:09.067
If there's no familial match, then
we know that Cam's in the clear.

08:09.069 --> 08:10.368
No, Brady, no.

08:10.370 --> 08:14.039
If my family is saying no, so am I.

08:17.977 --> 08:20.946
You don't need permission to
get a sample from your wife.

08:20.948 --> 08:24.082
Dana, do me a favor, don't
eavesdrop on my phone calls, okay?

08:24.084 --> 08:27.452
I was passing through,
happened to overhear.

08:27.454 --> 08:30.922
Different thing. Just saying.

08:30.924 --> 08:32.957
You live together.

08:32.960 --> 08:35.626
It's legal for you to take a
DNA sample from your own home.

08:35.629 --> 08:37.962
Now I know why you're divorced.

08:37.965 --> 08:40.198
Twice.

08:45.671 --> 08:49.474
He's unpredictable. I-I mean,
sometimes he's a normal kid.

08:49.476 --> 08:54.713
Other times it's like he's...
missing an empathy chip.

08:54.715 --> 08:59.851
He gave this weird speech
at my father's funeral.

08:59.853 --> 09:03.054
He tried to put his cousin in a cage.

09:03.056 --> 09:05.857
He... cut off a cat's tail.

09:05.859 --> 09:10.161
Not to hurt it, just to see
if the nerves would...

09:10.830 --> 09:11.896
regenerate.

09:11.898 --> 09:15.066
Um... you know, so we-we thought

09:15.068 --> 09:18.003
it would be a good idea for
him to see a professional.

09:18.005 --> 09:19.671
What would really help Jack is if

09:19.673 --> 09:21.539
his parents lived together
under the same roof again.

09:21.541 --> 09:24.776
(CHUCKLES): Well... well, we
were always fighting, I mean,

09:24.778 --> 09:26.478
that wasn't good for him.

09:26.480 --> 09:30.382
My mom died when I was ten, so
my dad sent me to a counselor.

09:30.384 --> 09:31.816
Pointless.

09:31.818 --> 09:34.419
Soph, she helped me when I was younger.

09:34.421 --> 09:37.422
If you'd like, I'd like
to try to help Jack.

09:39.042 --> 09:42.594
Come on. Let's give it a try.

09:44.830 --> 09:45.897
Fine.

09:45.899 --> 09:48.433
I just have some forms for you to sign,

09:48.435 --> 09:53.872
and I can fit Jack in tomorrow at...

09:53.874 --> 09:55.540
noon?

09:55.542 --> 09:58.476
This a consent form to
record the sessions?

09:58.478 --> 10:00.745
For liability purposes
because Jack is a minor.

10:00.747 --> 10:02.914
Did my mom have to sign
one of these for me?

10:02.916 --> 10:06.251
It's standard procedure
for underage clients.

10:06.253 --> 10:09.654
So... you recorded my sessions?

10:09.656 --> 10:11.389
Yes.

10:20.666 --> 10:22.333
SOPHIE: <i>What's wrong?</i>

10:22.335 --> 10:24.469
When I was a teenager I was
blitzed out of my mind.

10:24.471 --> 10:26.938
I said some weird stuff in
therapy, like dark stuff.

10:26.940 --> 10:28.106
Yeah, you're not the only one.

10:28.108 --> 10:29.507
No, it's...

10:29.509 --> 10:34.679
Brady found a photo of me from back then
wearing a belt like the one they found

10:34.681 --> 10:37.882
in the Silver Bells murder
that he's investigating.

10:37.884 --> 10:43.755
If the police do some digging
and find those tapes,

10:43.757 --> 10:45.523
it wouldn't look good.

10:47.293 --> 10:49.427
So, what now?

10:51.464 --> 10:53.832
I have to destroy those tapes.

10:53.834 --> 10:57.068
TESSA: <i>Cam's innocent.</i>
I know you know that.

10:57.070 --> 11:02.307
It's just such a weird situation, but we
shouldn't let it get between us, right?

11:02.309 --> 11:05.577
- I mean, we're first.
- Yes, we are.

11:05.579 --> 11:08.346
Okay, I'm late to meet
Lesley for a drink.

11:08.348 --> 11:10.982
- Love you big.
- Love you big.

11:13.627 --> 11:16.195
(SIGHS)

11:50.430 --> 11:53.249
BRADY: <i>Dana, I need you</i> to test one
of these hairs against the blood

11:53.274 --> 11:55.930
on the SBK belt, but I need
it done on the down-low.

11:56.352 --> 12:00.212
- How low we talking?
- Results can come to me and only me.

12:06.219 --> 12:07.453
(SIGHS)

12:07.455 --> 12:09.522
NAOMI: Great to see you here, Tom.

12:09.524 --> 12:12.258
TOM: I have an idea on how
to win back the youth vote.

12:12.260 --> 12:16.495
One of my old hedge fund buddies,
he's launching a mobile gaming app.

12:16.497 --> 12:19.732
I can reach out, see if we can
get some sponsored content.

12:19.734 --> 12:22.702
70% of mobile gamers are under 18.

12:22.704 --> 12:26.439
We need voters... of voting age.

12:26.441 --> 12:29.942
I was thinking about Stephen Gostkowski.

12:29.944 --> 12:31.777
The kicker for the Patriots?

12:31.779 --> 12:33.746
His "Q" rating with the 18-to-25

12:33.748 --> 12:38.084
set is astronomical, and he just
met with a political consultant.

12:38.086 --> 12:41.087
He's considering running for office.

12:41.089 --> 12:42.588
And what better way to dip his toes

12:42.590 --> 12:44.490
in the political waters
than by endorsing you?

12:44.492 --> 12:45.624
I'd swing up three points, at least.

12:45.626 --> 12:46.892
Yeah, we just need a way to woo him.

12:46.894 --> 12:50.196
Well, he's wearing a charity bracelet
for the Boston Arts Education Program.

12:50.198 --> 12:52.098
- How do you...?
- Well, Tessa's on the board.

12:52.100 --> 12:55.000
Could you fast-track a
fund-raiser for the program?

12:55.002 --> 12:57.169
How's Friday night?

13:00.140 --> 13:02.041
Well, we'll need some Patriots gear

13:02.043 --> 13:04.143
around the house so
Stephen knows we're fans.

13:04.145 --> 13:06.812
Great, yes, Tom, we could
use your help with that.

13:06.814 --> 13:13.652
THERAPIST: <i>Tell me how you're feeling.</i> I
know you're dealing with a lot right now:

13:13.654 --> 13:17.857
your parents living in two different
places, your grandpa's death.

13:17.859 --> 13:22.094
It's okay if you're not
comfortable talking to me yet...

13:22.096 --> 13:26.432
but I know someone you might
feel right at home with.

13:27.567 --> 13:30.703
Jack, meet Jake.

13:30.705 --> 13:34.140
Jake's parents have
been fighting, and that

13:34.142 --> 13:36.375
makes him want to do things
to get their attention.

13:37.611 --> 13:40.346
I don't talk to inanimate objects.

13:40.348 --> 13:46.385
My cousin Harper plays with dolls
and, honestly, it's super dumb.

13:46.387 --> 13:50.256
Also, your puppet is not
anatomically correct.

13:50.258 --> 13:52.458
Where are his teeth?

13:53.426 --> 13:55.628
(EXHALES)

14:02.803 --> 14:05.004
(BEEPING)

14:28.795 --> 14:30.629
"7862."

14:30.631 --> 14:31.730
What's that?

14:31.732 --> 14:35.701
The code to the delivery entrance
in the back of the building.

14:37.370 --> 14:39.371
How'd you do that?

14:41.007 --> 14:44.210
TESSA: <i>I'm impressed.</i>
A major fund-raiser.

14:44.212 --> 14:47.313
Only you could pull this off
with such short notice.

14:47.315 --> 14:51.116
It's good to have a project.
The house seems...

14:51.118 --> 14:53.619
so quiet.

14:55.856 --> 14:58.457
(ANIMAL SCREECHING)

15:00.427 --> 15:02.161
Is that a raccoon?

15:02.163 --> 15:05.164
Oh, God, it's stuck.

15:05.166 --> 15:07.132
(TESSA SHOUTS)

15:09.569 --> 15:11.203
Gunther?

15:11.205 --> 15:13.005
He's been giving me the creeps lately.

15:38.265 --> 15:40.499
WAITRESS: Here you go.

15:56.883 --> 15:58.951
WOMAN: Garrett.

16:04.157 --> 16:06.558
Molly.

16:10.363 --> 16:12.898
I-I heard about your dad.

16:12.900 --> 16:16.568
- I'm so sorry.
- Yeah.

16:18.705 --> 16:22.107
- Thanks.
- What?

16:22.109 --> 16:24.543
- You look e-exactly the same.
- Excuse me.

16:26.046 --> 16:28.747
So, are you back in Boston for good?

16:28.749 --> 16:32.351
Uh... I'm not sure. I don't know.

16:32.353 --> 16:34.119
I Googled you a couple years ago.

16:34.121 --> 16:36.689
You might be the only person I know

16:36.691 --> 16:38.757
with zero social media footprint.

16:38.759 --> 16:40.826
I don't... I don't know what that means.

16:40.828 --> 16:43.228
(CHUCKLES)

16:43.230 --> 16:45.397
- Pardon me.
- Right.

16:47.000 --> 16:49.468
Well, it's really good to see you.
I should, uh...

16:49.470 --> 16:52.671
No. I have some questions.

16:54.307 --> 16:56.942
You at least owe me that.

17:11.758 --> 17:14.859
What are you doing in there?

17:14.862 --> 17:17.329
I was looking for this.

17:24.570 --> 17:27.106
What the hell was that with the raccoon?

17:28.708 --> 17:30.743
He couldn't be saved.

17:30.745 --> 17:33.679
No reason to prolong his death, right?

17:35.782 --> 17:40.352
Nobody should have to
die in a cage, anyway.

17:44.958 --> 17:46.358
Gunther?

17:48.128 --> 17:49.695
This is your last day.

17:58.371 --> 18:00.773
GARRETT: <i>How you been?</i>

18:00.775 --> 18:03.642
MOLLY: <i>Not bad.</i>

18:03.644 --> 18:06.612
- You?
- Mm, good.

18:06.614 --> 18:10.115
You married?

18:10.117 --> 18:11.583
Huh? Kids?

18:11.585 --> 18:12.684
No, you know what?

18:12.686 --> 18:14.553
This is not... not how this goes.

18:14.555 --> 18:17.656
You do not get to hide
behind questions about me,

18:17.658 --> 18:20.492
'cause the last time I
saw you, we were talking

18:20.494 --> 18:21.994
about shopping for rings,

18:21.996 --> 18:23.495
then you were gone.

18:25.665 --> 18:28.734
The same guy who courted me
with surprise takeout from

18:28.736 --> 18:30.869
my favorite Chinese hole-in-the-wall,

18:30.871 --> 18:34.173
sang me to sleep after I
had to put my dog down.

18:35.175 --> 18:36.308
You vanished.

18:36.310 --> 18:37.976
No call...

18:37.978 --> 18:40.579
no nothing.

18:40.581 --> 18:42.481
I asked your friends, your family.

18:42.483 --> 18:44.750
Nobody knew where you went or why you...

18:44.752 --> 18:47.219
♪ Oh

18:47.221 --> 18:49.521
So, then I thought...

18:49.523 --> 18:50.489
maybe it was me.

18:50.491 --> 18:51.757
No.

18:51.759 --> 18:53.492
♪ Can't get my feet on the floor ♪

18:53.494 --> 18:54.526
No.

18:54.528 --> 18:56.095
Here's the part

18:56.097 --> 18:58.730
where you tell me why you left.

18:58.732 --> 19:00.199
♪ I've been living in my head

19:00.201 --> 19:02.334
♪ I can't get my feet on the floor... ♪

19:02.336 --> 19:04.603
Before I left, there were...

19:04.605 --> 19:07.706
there were things happening

19:07.708 --> 19:08.941
that I couldn't...

19:08.943 --> 19:11.243
I couldn't...

19:13.046 --> 19:17.649
Everyone had this idea of...

19:17.651 --> 19:20.185
who they thought I was gonna be.

19:20.187 --> 19:21.653
Uh, the golden boy

19:21.655 --> 19:24.723
who takes over the family
business, you know.

19:24.725 --> 19:27.326
I was never gonna be that guy.

19:28.995 --> 19:31.096
I just... I couldn't pretend anymore.

19:31.098 --> 19:34.399
♪ I've been living in my head... ♪

19:34.401 --> 19:35.834
If that's the explanation

19:35.836 --> 19:37.703
you're gonna give me after 14 years,

19:37.705 --> 19:40.005
don't think for a minute I
am just going to nod my head

19:40.007 --> 19:41.507
and say, "Now I understand everything,"

19:41.509 --> 19:43.509
and ask you to join my book club.

19:43.511 --> 19:47.079
♪ I can't get my feet on the floor ♪

19:49.249 --> 19:52.017
♪ I've been living in my head

19:52.019 --> 19:53.619
(SIGHS) Uh...

19:53.621 --> 19:55.487
♪ I can't get my feet on the floor ♪

19:57.757 --> 20:01.160
Do you still like cashew chicken?

20:01.162 --> 20:03.829
♪ Can't get my feet on the floor ♪

20:03.831 --> 20:05.097
Extra cashews.

20:05.099 --> 20:06.198
We could... we could

20:06.200 --> 20:08.267
go to the Chinese place,

20:08.269 --> 20:10.736
maybe?

20:10.738 --> 20:14.139
♪ Can't get my feet on the floor. ♪

20:14.141 --> 20:15.974
Maybe.

20:33.326 --> 20:35.894
(CAT MEOWS)

20:39.732 --> 20:42.601
Caramel.

20:42.603 --> 20:45.204
(CAT MEOWS)

20:45.838 --> 20:48.373
Caramel.

20:51.344 --> 20:55.147
Here, Caramel.

21:03.189 --> 21:05.390
(BEEPING)

21:32.185 --> 21:35.454
♪

22:00.280 --> 22:03.548
♪

22:27.807 --> 22:32.744
It kind of... it kind of feels
like I'm floating, you know?

22:32.746 --> 22:36.048
I can feel every cell in my body.

22:36.050 --> 22:39.151
(LAUGHING): It's awesome.

22:40.286 --> 22:42.788
I'm not high this time,

22:42.790 --> 22:44.389
if that's what you were thinking.

22:44.391 --> 22:45.991
I wasn't thinking that, Cam.

22:45.993 --> 22:47.759
Yes, you were.

22:47.761 --> 22:50.329
But that's okay. People
assume the worst of me.

22:54.801 --> 22:57.536
Cam, you're shaking.

23:01.974 --> 23:04.209
I-I want to talk about the body.

23:25.502 --> 23:26.702
Stop.

23:26.704 --> 23:28.136
Sit.

23:28.138 --> 23:30.606
Don't make me talk to
you like you're a dog.

23:30.608 --> 23:32.508
What is your deal?

23:32.510 --> 23:35.978
(WHISPERING): It's weird being
here after breaking in here.

23:35.980 --> 23:37.513
(SIGHS) What if I messed up?

23:37.515 --> 23:39.214
I feel like we're going to get caught.

23:39.216 --> 23:41.283
You won't.

23:41.285 --> 23:43.552
THERAPIST: <i>I thought this time</i>

23:43.554 --> 23:44.887
we might try something different.

23:44.889 --> 23:46.855
Me, too.

23:46.857 --> 23:48.457
I even brought my own puppet.

23:48.459 --> 23:51.360
Oh, that's very nice, Jack.

23:51.362 --> 23:52.794
Let's see it.

23:54.731 --> 23:58.100
You want to come over tonight?

24:03.973 --> 24:05.574
I have plans.

24:08.444 --> 24:09.411
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

24:09.413 --> 24:11.446
What?

24:11.448 --> 24:12.748
What's going on?

24:12.750 --> 24:14.416
I can't continue seeing Jack.

24:14.418 --> 24:16.685
Look, I'll be happy to e-mail you

24:16.687 --> 24:19.588
the names of some therapists
whose areas of expertise

24:19.590 --> 24:22.658
are more in line with his areas of...

24:22.660 --> 24:24.026
Good luck to you.

24:28.531 --> 24:31.266
My son just got fired by his therapist.

24:40.376 --> 24:42.711
(BACH'S "CELLO SUITE NO.
1 IN G MAJOR" PLAYING)

24:48.818 --> 24:51.019
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

24:55.191 --> 24:56.425
It's quite a turnout.

24:56.427 --> 24:58.093
Excellent.

24:58.095 --> 25:00.696
We may need Gunther to
bring in more seating.

25:00.698 --> 25:02.698
I fired Gunther.

25:02.700 --> 25:03.999
What? You did?

25:04.001 --> 25:05.968
I had to.

25:05.970 --> 25:09.304
I've been getting this really
weird feeling from him lately,

25:09.306 --> 25:13.642
and, well, then there was
this incident that...

25:13.644 --> 25:15.077
Now's not the time.

25:15.079 --> 25:17.412
- Let's just enjoy this.
- (DOORBELL CHIMING)

25:17.414 --> 25:18.747
Oh, look.

25:18.749 --> 25:21.550
WOMAN: Stephen Gostkowski is here.

25:26.122 --> 25:28.390
ALISON: Hi, Stephen. Great to see you.

25:28.392 --> 25:29.858
You remember Naomi?

25:31.928 --> 25:35.864
NAOMI: We're expecting maximum
attendance around 8:00 p.m.

25:35.866 --> 25:37.699
Madeline will introduce Alison,
who will say a few words,

25:37.701 --> 25:38.967
and hand over the floor to you.

25:38.969 --> 25:40.435
You draw up the play and I'll run it.

25:40.437 --> 25:41.737
That's what I'm used to.

25:41.739 --> 25:43.939
Great. Let me introduce you around.

25:53.750 --> 25:55.384
There it is.

25:55.386 --> 25:58.720
Well, this is incredibly weird.

25:58.722 --> 26:00.589
You were right.

26:00.591 --> 26:02.257
So you want to...

26:02.259 --> 26:05.227
What? You eager to go downstairs
and schmooze with donors?

26:05.229 --> 26:07.596
No.

26:07.598 --> 26:09.798
Cashew chicken.

26:11.000 --> 26:13.168
Wow, this is...

26:13.170 --> 26:14.936
so different.

26:14.938 --> 26:17.506
The bed was over here.

26:17.508 --> 26:18.707
Remember that?

26:18.709 --> 26:20.976
Yeah. I remember everything.

26:22.011 --> 26:25.113
(CHUCKLES)

26:30.420 --> 26:31.653
You kept these?

26:31.655 --> 26:33.088
- (MUMBLING)
- Hey.

26:33.090 --> 26:34.256
(LAUGHS)

27:00.016 --> 27:03.285
♪

27:22.772 --> 27:25.574
What are these?

27:25.576 --> 27:28.143
- Scars.
- No.

27:28.145 --> 27:29.444
I know.

27:29.446 --> 27:30.812
Wh... how did you get them?

27:30.814 --> 27:32.080
What does it matter how I got them?

27:32.082 --> 27:33.982
'Cause it matters.

27:33.984 --> 27:35.117
- Tell me.
- It doesn't matter.

27:35.119 --> 27:37.285
It... because it matters.

27:37.287 --> 27:38.887
Stop!

27:40.857 --> 27:42.691
Molly.

27:43.693 --> 27:45.894
Don't touch me.

27:49.419 --> 27:52.521
I went to that stupid coffee
shop three days in a row.

27:52.836 --> 27:54.302
What?

27:56.472 --> 27:58.807
Your mom told me...

28:00.209 --> 28:02.744
I don't know what I was thinking.

28:07.049 --> 28:08.283
MADELINE: <i>Cheers.</i>

28:08.285 --> 28:09.618
ALISON: <i>Let's toast</i>

28:09.620 --> 28:11.887
once the endorsement's official.

28:11.889 --> 28:13.288
Oh, we will.

28:13.290 --> 28:14.890
But this one's for the
offer I just accepted

28:14.892 --> 28:16.358
for Hawthorne Concrete.

28:16.360 --> 28:17.459
Already.

28:17.461 --> 28:18.593
Big company out of Moscow.

28:18.595 --> 28:19.661
Darcolo.

28:19.663 --> 28:21.930
No mixed feelings?

28:21.932 --> 28:23.532
It's the end of an era.

28:23.534 --> 28:25.433
It's a ruthless business.

28:25.435 --> 28:29.738
And there's certain skeletons
that I'm glad to be rid of.

28:29.740 --> 28:31.139
And...

28:31.141 --> 28:33.241
your campaign will get a big infusion

28:33.243 --> 28:35.110
of capital at a critical time.

28:36.879 --> 28:39.147
(DOORBELL CHIMING)

28:39.149 --> 28:42.250
Oh, if it's that lady and her cat...

28:43.753 --> 28:46.188
ALISON: What the hell?

28:46.989 --> 28:49.257
Did you invite Mayor Conley?

28:49.259 --> 28:51.092
Of course not.

28:51.094 --> 28:54.029
I'll handle this.

28:54.831 --> 28:57.199
Mmm.

28:58.034 --> 29:00.368
Can I get you anything else?

29:00.370 --> 29:04.172
You're probably wondering
what I'm doing here.

29:04.174 --> 29:07.843
One, the stuffed mushrooms.

29:07.845 --> 29:09.311
Two...

29:16.586 --> 29:18.053
NAOMI: What is this?

29:18.055 --> 29:19.654
Your brother breaking
into a medical facility

29:19.656 --> 29:21.723
in Longwood last night.

29:21.725 --> 29:23.191
You were stalking him?

29:23.193 --> 29:25.126
Stalking, opposition research.

29:25.128 --> 29:26.561
It's a fine line.

29:26.563 --> 29:28.330
I'm sure he had a good
reason for being there.

29:28.332 --> 29:29.564
Wearing a baseball cap?

29:29.566 --> 29:30.999
Going through a delivery entrance

29:31.001 --> 29:32.701
of a medical building at 1:00 a.m.?

29:32.703 --> 29:35.303
A medical building that
houses pharmaceuticals?

29:35.305 --> 29:36.938
What do you suppose a former junkie

29:36.940 --> 29:39.107
was doing inside there for 45 minutes?

29:39.109 --> 29:40.675
Go ahead. Amuse me.

29:40.677 --> 29:41.943
Hazard a guess.

29:41.945 --> 29:43.612
What do you want?

29:43.614 --> 29:45.380
Give up the Stephen
Gostkowski endorsement.

29:45.382 --> 29:47.983
Just tell him you're no longer
in the market for his support,

29:47.985 --> 29:50.552
'cause if he goes anywhere
near that podium tonight,

29:50.554 --> 29:53.088
these pictures will be
in tomorrow's paper.

30:01.631 --> 30:03.932
What is this?

30:03.934 --> 30:05.934
What the hell?

30:05.936 --> 30:07.962
You're breaking into
places to steal drugs now?

30:07.987 --> 30:08.637
What? No.

30:08.639 --> 30:10.805
- I wasn't there to steal drugs.
- Then why were you there?

30:10.807 --> 30:12.440
It's complicated.

30:12.442 --> 30:13.893
I left something there,
and I had to go get it.

30:13.917 --> 30:14.376
(SCOFFS)

30:14.378 --> 30:16.278
- You're lying.
- I'm not. Where'd you get this, anyway?

30:16.280 --> 30:18.880
- Are you having me followed?
- Conley's people took them.

30:18.882 --> 30:21.016
And if Stephen Gostkowski
endorses me tonight,

30:21.018 --> 30:22.484
he's going to take them to the press.

30:22.486 --> 30:24.519
You can't.

30:24.521 --> 30:27.188
They'll arrest me. I'll lose Jack.
You got to help me out.

30:27.190 --> 30:29.824
You did this to yourself. You.

30:29.826 --> 30:31.226
No, no, no, please.

30:31.228 --> 30:32.727
We're out of time, Alison.

30:32.729 --> 30:35.530
We have to get down there.

30:52.027 --> 30:53.799
Thank you all for coming here tonight.

30:53.824 --> 30:55.690
And thank you for your
generous contributions

30:55.715 --> 30:59.066
to the Boston Arts Education Program.

30:59.121 --> 31:01.331
At a time when teachers

31:01.356 --> 31:03.301
are forced to use test scores

31:03.326 --> 31:06.527
to assess the quality
of public education,

31:06.529 --> 31:09.697
it's more important than
ever that we defend

31:09.699 --> 31:12.032
our children's ability to create.

31:12.034 --> 31:14.735
- You okay?
- Yeah.

31:14.737 --> 31:16.070
Now, we have some

31:16.072 --> 31:17.604
incredible people here tonight

31:17.606 --> 31:19.273
to support this cause.

31:26.114 --> 31:28.716
One of whom is

31:28.718 --> 31:30.317
Mayor Bill Conley.

31:32.721 --> 31:35.456
Come on up here, Bill.

31:38.893 --> 31:43.097
Mayor Conley and I just had
a private conversation,

31:43.099 --> 31:46.667
which I'd like to share.

31:51.673 --> 31:54.575
We just talked about the fact that

31:54.577 --> 31:56.310
despite our differences,

31:56.312 --> 31:59.046
we can reach across the aisle

31:59.048 --> 32:01.181
when it comes to our kids

32:01.183 --> 32:04.251
and their education,
especially in the arts.

32:04.253 --> 32:07.821
As the proud sister of
a professional artist,

32:07.823 --> 32:12.025
I've seen firsthand how
effective arts education

32:12.027 --> 32:16.263
can be in helping young
people forge successful,

32:16.265 --> 32:18.499
creative careers.

32:18.501 --> 32:21.135
(CROWD APPLAUDS)

32:21.137 --> 32:22.603
CAM: <i>Thank you, I-I promise you</i>

32:22.605 --> 32:24.571
I wasn't there to get drugs.

32:24.573 --> 32:26.073
Stop.

32:26.075 --> 32:28.342
How many times have you
promised no more drugs,

32:28.344 --> 32:31.979
you're better, it's
over, how many times?

32:31.981 --> 32:35.416
How much do the rest of
us have to sacrifice?

32:35.418 --> 32:37.418
That endorsement could have

32:37.420 --> 32:40.554
sealed the election for me.

32:42.290 --> 32:44.825
So, tell me what to do, Cam.

32:44.827 --> 32:47.327
Tell me...

32:47.329 --> 32:49.797
'cause you've been a mess
since you were a kid,

32:49.799 --> 32:52.466
and now Jack's following
in your footsteps, so

32:52.468 --> 32:54.301
what do we do?

32:56.137 --> 32:58.705
I've tried tough love,

32:58.707 --> 33:00.607
Tessa's tried coddling,

33:00.609 --> 33:03.544
Mom's tried shipping you
off to the most expensive

33:03.546 --> 33:05.612
rehab facility in this state.

33:05.614 --> 33:08.549
How do we fix you?

33:12.520 --> 33:14.621
Or is it just...

33:14.623 --> 33:17.257
not possible?

33:20.428 --> 33:22.996
You don't need to be fixed.

33:22.998 --> 33:25.666
Your family doesn't get you.

33:27.702 --> 33:29.736
I get you.

33:30.839 --> 33:34.608
You want to stay for a late night snack?

33:39.481 --> 33:42.282
What if I just stayed?

34:00.869 --> 34:02.603
Dang.

34:02.605 --> 34:04.338
Yeah?

34:04.340 --> 34:07.774
Oh, no, I said "dang," not Dana.

34:07.776 --> 34:09.243
Oh.

34:09.245 --> 34:10.944
My name's only one letter away.

34:10.946 --> 34:12.779
You know what else?

34:12.781 --> 34:16.683
It's also only one letter away from DNA.

34:16.685 --> 34:18.418
(CHUCKLES)

34:18.420 --> 34:19.920
This job is my destiny.

34:19.922 --> 34:21.420
Cool.

34:21.422 --> 34:23.422
I have news, by the way.

34:23.425 --> 34:25.626
The full report will take
a few days, but, uh,

34:25.628 --> 34:28.661
give you the headline.

34:35.637 --> 34:36.637
Hey, buddy.

34:36.639 --> 34:37.737
Hey.

34:37.739 --> 34:38.804
Can't sleep?

34:38.806 --> 34:40.908
I could, but it was boring.

34:40.909 --> 34:43.010
What are you watching?

34:43.012 --> 34:45.712
Something boring.

34:45.714 --> 34:47.214
Can I watch, too?

34:47.216 --> 34:49.416
Sure.

34:49.418 --> 34:51.752
Hey, so...

34:51.754 --> 34:54.420
what happened today at
the therapist's office?

34:55.723 --> 34:57.758
She didn't like my puppet.

34:57.760 --> 35:00.093
What puppet?

35:00.095 --> 35:02.930
I'll show you.

35:17.345 --> 35:20.013
Thanks, Phyllis.

35:20.015 --> 35:23.216
Now I have teeth.

35:28.690 --> 35:31.024
(DOORBELL CHIMING)

35:31.026 --> 35:32.859
What the hell?

35:36.998 --> 35:39.199
We need to talk, Mrs. Hawthorne.

35:39.201 --> 35:40.634
Oh, well, whatever it is,

35:40.636 --> 35:42.402
I'm sure it can wait till tomorrow.

35:42.404 --> 35:43.804
No.

35:43.806 --> 35:46.506
It's about the Silver Bells case.

35:55.416 --> 35:57.250
- Give us a moment, please.
- Of course.

36:00.488 --> 36:02.255
All right, well,

36:02.257 --> 36:03.523
now that you've made a scene...

36:03.525 --> 36:04.658
That wasn't my intention.

36:04.660 --> 36:05.859
What do you want?

36:05.861 --> 36:07.160
The, uh,

36:07.162 --> 36:08.295
leather belt we pulled

36:08.297 --> 36:10.163
from the collapsed tunnel,

36:10.165 --> 36:12.065
the one we believe the
Silver Bells Killer

36:12.067 --> 36:13.734
used to strangle his last victim,

36:13.736 --> 36:15.068
turns out you purchased a belt

36:15.070 --> 36:16.970
just like it a month before the murder.

36:16.972 --> 36:18.772
BRADY: Detective Cutter.

36:18.774 --> 36:20.540
I am in the middle of
something, Detective Ross.

36:20.542 --> 36:22.476
This family is not connected to

36:22.478 --> 36:23.644
the Silver Bells killings.

36:23.646 --> 36:24.745
That is still to be determined.

36:24.747 --> 36:26.013
No, I tested their DNA

36:26.015 --> 36:27.748
and the report shows
no match to the belt.

36:28.983 --> 36:31.451
LINDA: So, I guess it's
just a coincidence

36:31.453 --> 36:33.553
that the type of belt you owned wound up

36:33.555 --> 36:35.756
in concrete made by your company.

36:35.758 --> 36:38.825
No, not a coincidence.

36:38.827 --> 36:42.763
One of my longtime household
staffers, Gunther Holzmann,

36:42.765 --> 36:46.366
had access to both the
belt and the work site,

36:46.368 --> 36:49.302
and as much as it hurts me to say so,

36:49.304 --> 36:50.904
I think you should look into him.

36:50.906 --> 36:52.039
And where is he?

36:52.041 --> 36:53.940
I terminated his employment yesterday,

36:53.942 --> 36:55.776
but I can give you his address.

36:57.745 --> 37:00.013
- Where did you get the sample?
- What?

37:00.015 --> 37:02.949
To test the DNA, you needed a sample.
Where did you get it?

37:02.951 --> 37:05.952
I-I-I took a hair from your hairbrush.

37:05.954 --> 37:07.254
What?

37:07.256 --> 37:08.855
Tess, technically, it's legal without

37:08.857 --> 37:09.990
your consent because
it's from our own home.

37:09.992 --> 37:11.358
"Technically legal"?

37:11.360 --> 37:12.726
I don't care if it's legal.

37:12.728 --> 37:13.760
I said no.

37:13.762 --> 37:15.262
No, Tess, I know, but...

37:15.264 --> 37:16.763
come on, you got to look at
the bigger picture here.

37:16.765 --> 37:18.131
I just exonerated your family.

37:18.133 --> 37:20.500
You betrayed my trust.

37:20.502 --> 37:22.202
We talked about this, we agreed,

37:22.204 --> 37:24.571
and then you went behind my back.

37:24.573 --> 37:26.773
Get out.

37:26.775 --> 37:28.308
What?

37:28.310 --> 37:30.777
I'm staying here tonight.

37:50.104 --> 37:51.203
What's going on?

37:51.205 --> 37:54.307
Business trip, Moscow, back Thursday.

37:56.410 --> 37:57.710
It was you.

37:57.712 --> 38:00.413
You bought Hawthorne Concrete.

38:00.415 --> 38:02.870
Well, technically,
Darcolo Industries did,

38:02.972 --> 38:05.039
but I will be running it.

38:06.581 --> 38:08.415
I love you, Ali,

38:08.417 --> 38:10.818
but I'm done being your lackey.

38:10.820 --> 38:14.955
Consider this my officially
tendered resignation.

38:18.878 --> 38:22.614
ALISON: <i>I thought I had
everything managed...</i>

38:22.800 --> 38:26.502
but now I just...

38:27.378 --> 38:29.880
I feel powerless.

38:29.882 --> 38:32.151
My marriage, my campaign...

38:32.206 --> 38:35.371
Alison, in one night
you saved your brother

38:35.396 --> 38:37.697
from a probable arrest,

38:37.699 --> 38:40.833
you raised $60,000 in arts education,

38:40.835 --> 38:43.136
and you looked killer in that dress.

38:43.138 --> 38:44.770
(LAUGHS)

38:44.772 --> 38:46.839
You think?

38:48.575 --> 38:50.343
I do.

39:16.570 --> 39:18.437
You orchestrated this whole thing

39:18.439 --> 39:19.705
with Molly.

39:23.277 --> 39:25.111
Why?

39:26.346 --> 39:27.747
I wanted to show you

39:27.749 --> 39:29.949
what's good about this life

39:29.951 --> 39:32.985
so you wouldn't want to destroy it.

39:32.987 --> 39:35.688
It almost worked.

39:37.291 --> 39:40.326
Still could.

39:40.328 --> 39:43.129
I want you to be happy.

39:43.131 --> 39:46.032
You want my silence.

39:46.034 --> 39:48.634
Can't I want both?

39:52.306 --> 39:53.639
Garrett.

39:55.209 --> 39:57.310
You need to make peace
with the past in a way

39:57.312 --> 39:59.312
that's not destructive.

40:05.352 --> 40:08.854
I don't know if I can.

40:28.842 --> 40:31.410
(GRUNTS)

40:39.786 --> 40:41.787
And you did this chopping carrots?

40:41.789 --> 40:44.657
Mm-hmm.

40:44.659 --> 40:47.493
Maybe get the bag of
baby carrots next time.

40:47.495 --> 40:49.729
Hmm...

40:49.731 --> 40:51.097
a good idea.

40:51.099 --> 40:53.645
I'm lucky this place was nearby.

40:54.559 --> 40:55.801
You live around here?

40:57.192 --> 40:58.450
Yeah, pretty close.

40:58.731 --> 41:00.130
You?

41:00.132 --> 41:02.199
Not far.

41:02.201 --> 41:05.502
I feel like, uh...

41:05.504 --> 41:08.238
I feel like I've seen you before.

41:09.941 --> 41:12.743
Yeah, maybe the news.

41:12.745 --> 41:15.979
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

41:17.515 --> 41:19.216
Your father...

41:21.419 --> 41:23.186
Yeah, my father was

41:23.188 --> 41:25.455
a victim of the Silver Bells Killer...

41:27.191 --> 41:30.660
...but they're closing in
on the guy now, finally.

41:34.399 --> 41:36.266
That is good news.

41:37.902 --> 41:39.469
(WHISPERING): Yeah.

41:41.039 --> 41:43.040
TESSA: <i>It does feel like the killer</i>

41:43.042 --> 41:45.509
<i>could be someone close to us,</i>

41:45.511 --> 41:48.612
